close_symbols: semantics of the req_cls request-class parameter (libmicrohttpd: initial value, persistence across callback invocations)
explanation:
To determine whether any portion of ahc_echo is unreachable you must know the exact values, types and runtime semantics of the symbols that control its control-flow and conditional branches: 

- MHD_DigestAuthResult (enum type): required to interpret the return of MHD_digest_auth_check3 and understand which enum values are possible. 
- MHD_DAUTH_OK and MHD_DAUTH_NONCE_STALE: the code branches on (res_e != MHD_DAUTH_OK) and (res_e == MHD_DAUTH_NONCE_STALE); you need their definitions to know whether those comparisons can be true or false. 
- MHD_digest_auth_check3: its prototype and documented possible return values/behavior are needed to reason whether the authentication branch (deny vs allow) is reachable. 
- MHD_queue_auth_required_response3: used in the deny branch and returns ret; its prototype/behavior (including whether it may not return) is required to know if subsequent code can execute. 
- MHD_create_response_from_buffer_static: used both in deny and allow branches; you need to know whether it can return NULL or always succeeds (affects reachability of early return paths). 
- MHD_queue_response: used in the allow branch and provides the final return value; its behavior/signature is required to reason about that path being taken and returned from. 
- MHD_destroy_response: called after queuing responses; its behavior (normal return, side effects) is relevant to ensure no non-returning behavior makes following code unreachable. 
- DENIED and PAGE (string constants): the code invokes strlen(DENIED) and constructs responses from these buffers; presence/definitions are needed to confirm those branches are meaningful. 
- MY_OPAQUE_STR: passed to queue_auth_required_response3; its presence/definition may affect the call but primarily included to fully understand the deny-branch call. 
- MHD_DIGEST_AUTH_MULT_QOP_ANY_NON_INT and MHD_DIGEST_AUTH_MULT_ALGO3_ANY_NON_SESSION: macros passed to the auth check and auth-required response; their values could affect digest-check behavior or be required to understand whether certain auth outcomes are possible. 
- MHD_Result values (MHD_YES, MHD_NO, MHD_HTTP_OK): used as return values; needed to reason about which return paths are taken and whether some returns make following code unreachable. 
- semantics of the req_cls request-class parameter: the very first if-statement compares *req_cls to &already_called_marker and returns MHD_YES on the first invocation. To decide whether the remainder of the function is reachable you must know how libmicrohttpd initializes and preserves req_cls between callback invocations (typically NULL on first call and preserved across subsequent calls). If req_cls is always set to &already_called_marker before the other code runs, large portions would be unreachable; conversely, if libmicrohttpd guarantees the two-invocation pattern, the later code is reachable on the second invocation.

Together these symbols (types, enum values, function behaviors and req_cls semantics) provide the necessary information to decide whether any branch or statement in ahc_echo can never be executed (i.e. would be MISRA 'unreachable code').
